8457F177-72B8-495C-B502-18A1EC2E4EFD</gtr:id><gtr:name>Flinders University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Flinders University</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Sturt Road, Bedford Park</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>GPO Box 2100</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Adelaide</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>5001</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Outside UK</gtr:region><gtr:country>Australia</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/D0FE4F64-6F5A-44E8-9BB1-FE5B18D3F004"><gtr:id>D0FE4F64-6F5A-44E8-9BB1-FE5B18D3F004</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Katherine</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Stevens</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G106%2F1237"><gtr:id>8068104C-49EB-4A9F-887B-61D83CC44D39</gtr:id><gtr:title>The development of a paediatric health related quality of life measure for use in economic evaluation.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G106/1237</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Making decisions amongst competing healthcare needs is important in the UK NHS. In order to make more informed decisions, information is needed on the costs and benefits of alternative treatments. We can use an economic evaluation to compare these costs and benefits. In addition to increasing length of life, many treatments have an impact on quality of life and this benfit can be combined into a single measure called the quality adjusted life year (QALY). Treatments can then be compared in terms of their cost per QALY gained. Instruments that measure this quality of life have been developed for adults and each has a set of preference weights associated with them which have been derived from interviews with the general public. These give a higher weight to more desirable health states. Instruments that measure health related quality of life for children that can be used in this way are lacking. This research is developing a new health related quality of life measure for children that can measure QALYs gained and is therefore suitable for use in economic evaluation. This should lead to better and more informed decision making in healthcare for children.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The aim of the research is to develop a preference based paediatric health related quality of life measure for use in economic evaluation. This measure will improve and assist decision making in the NHS, by allowing comparison of interventions using a common metric. The research consists of two distinct stages. The first stage is the development of a descriptive system and the second is to develop preference weights. Existing work in the area will be reviewed and existing measures evaluated in terms of their suitability for use in economic evaluation. Parents, children and decision makers will be interviewed in order to identify candidate dimensions for the instrument. The primary consideration will be what areas they consider to be important enough to warrant allocation of public resources to. The results of these interviews will form a pool of candidate dimensions. Levels will be developed for each dimension, using further interviews and the literature as a guide. When valuing health states, individuals can only process a limited amount of information, therefore the final instrument is constrained in terms of the number of dimensions it can have. Ranking work will be carried out on the long list of dimensions in order to use preferences to determine the dimensions that will form a pilot instrument. This instrument will undergo psychometric testing to look at issues such as practicality and validity and revisions to the instrument will be made as necessary. The dimensions that form the instrument and their respective levels together make a classification system where a health state is defined as one level from each dimension. To make the instrument suitable for use in economic evaluation, preference weights need to be developed for the health states. The standard gamble (SG) technique will be used to value a sample of health states using a sample of the general population. Modelling will be used to produce values for every health state. This approach is an established method, used successfully in previous valuation work for the main adult instruments. 
The ordinal preference data obtained from the ranking exercise will be used to validate the SG model, by assessing whether the model predictions are consistent with the rank data and by comparing it to a model estimated from the rank data alone. This approach will draw on research on-going at ScHARR, and Harvard University in America, on the relationship between ordinal and cardinal health state preferences.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-08-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>156212</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Flinders University</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>Australia, Commonwealth of</gtr:country><gtr:department>Flinders Clinical Effectiveness Services</gtr:department><gtr:description>Flinders University</gtr:description><gtr:id>DCA66D1D-EDC2-4F44-9707-9846FDFDB46B</gtr:id><gtr:impact>3 peer reviewed publications - see other outputs and knowledge. Collaboration is not multi disciplinary.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>qDPfPk69fh4-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Work to undertake validation and valuation of the CHU9D in an Australian population.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>Collaborative visit to Flinders University November 2010. Joint working on research design, analysis and publication of research related to the use of the CHU9D in Australia.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>PHARMAC</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>87A31551-548